      Is Elon Musk=E2=80=99s drug use securities fraud?
   =20
 =20

We have   talked a few times over the years about the mysterious Tesla Inc.=
 lawyer=C2=A0whose court-mandated job is to review Elon Musk=E2=80=99s draf=
t tweets that might be material to Tesla shareholders. In theory, Musk has =
to show his tweets to this lawyer, and if the lawyer says =E2=80=9Cthis is =
material and misleading,=E2=80=9D Musk is supposed to not tweet it. In prac=
tice =E2=80=A6=C2=A0really? Musk is a volatile and demanding boss who tweet=
s impulsively at all hours and, what, you=E2=80=99re going to stop him? You=
=E2=80=99re not going to stop him. Terrible job. I don=E2=80=99t think anyo=
ne has  ever actually done it, and as far as I know whoever used to pretend=
 to do it has stopped.=C2=A0
Anyway here=E2=80=99s a worse job:
An attorney for Musk,=C2=A0Alex Spiro, said that Musk is =E2=80=9Cregularly=
 and randomly drug tested at SpaceX and has never failed a test.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
Not Alex Spiro=E2=80=99s job, I mean; Alex Spiro seems to be having fun. Bu=
t imagine being the SpaceX employee in charge of randomly drug testing Elon=
 Musk. Tiptoe=C2=A0into Musk=E2=80=99s office after his night out  not gett=
ing into Berghain=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Chey=C2=A0Mr. Musk it=E2=80=99s time=
 for your random drug test, here=E2=80=99s a cup.=E2=80=9D What if he says =
no? What if he hands you back the cup and it is just full of cocaine?=C2=A0=
What are you going to do about it? You work for him and he is not, like, a =
chill and understanding guy.
Spiro=E2=80=99s non-denial
  [1]
=C2=A0comes from  this Wall Street Journal story about how Elon Musk =E2=80=
=9Chas used LSD, cocaine, ecstasy and psychedelic mushrooms,=E2=80=9D as we=
ll as using ketamine recreationally, that =E2=80=9Chis drug use is ongoing,=
 especially his consumption of ketamine,=E2=80=9D that people close to him =
=E2=80=9Care concerned it could cause a health crisis,=E2=80=9D and that =
=E2=80=9Cillegal drug use would likely be a violation of federal policies t=
hat could jeopardize SpaceX=E2=80=99s billions of dollars in government con=
tracts.=E2=80=9D
I actually doubt that last part? I feel like Elon Musk=E2=80=99s recent car=
eer is a long experiment to prove that, if you are successful enough, the r=
egular laws do not apply to you. I assume that if Musk walked into the offi=
ce of the secretary of defense and snorted a bag of coke in front of him, n=
o government contracts would be canceled. =E2=80=9CDo you want to send up y=
our satellites on my good rockets, or do you want to enforce your rules abo=
ut drug use by government contractors,=E2=80=9D Musk is implicitly asking, =
and there is an obviously correct answer.=C2=A0Musk is too big to fail a dr=
ug test.
But Musk is also the chief executive officer of a public company, Tesla Inc=
., and you have to feel for Tesla=E2=80=99s board of directors:
=09On the one hand, Tesla does have policies against illegal drug use, and =
you could concoct a scenario in which Musk=E2=80=99s alleged drug use could=
 somehow harm Tesla, either because it gets him in trouble with customers o=
r regulators or just because being on drugs all the time makes him an errat=
ic decision maker.=C2=A0=09On the other hand, what are you gonna do about i=
t? Fire him? That=E2=80=99s much worse for Tesla, probably. Ask him to stop=
? Good luck with that.

One good actual answer to =E2=80=9Cwhat are you gonna do about it=E2=80=9D =
is =E2=80=9Cquit=E2=80=9D:
One former Tesla director, Linda Johnson Rice, grew so frustrated with Musk=
=E2=80=99s volatile behavior and her concerns about his drug consumption th=
at she didn=E2=80=99t stand for re-election to the electric-car company=E2=
=80=99s board in 2019, according to people familiar with the matter.
Reasonable. The other answer is =E2=80=9Ctalk about it in hushed, worried t=
ones,=E2=80=9D which is fine for talking about your friend=E2=80=99s drug u=
se, but actually legally problematic for a public company board of director=
s. The correct version of that answer is =E2=80=9Ctalk about it in hushed, =
worried tones, but not in a way that will make it into any official board m=
inutes that are later discoverable in litigation=E2=80=9D:

Some Tesla board members over the years have talked among themselves about =
their concerns over Musk=E2=80=99s alleged drug use but haven=E2=80=99t sai=
d anything formally that would end up as an official board agenda item or i=
n meeting minutes, people familiar with the discussions said. Some director=
s, including current Tesla board chair=C2=A0Robyn Denholm, have gone to Kim=
bal Musk, who is a Tesla board member and was a SpaceX board member until e=
arly 2022, for help with Musk=E2=80=99s behavior, without using the word =
=E2=80=9Cdrugs,=E2=80=9D the people said. =E2=80=A6
At Tesla, Denholm, the current board chair, James Murdoch and other directo=
rs sometimes gathered around Kimbal Musk informally during board breaks or =
after meetings to ask how Elon Musk was doing or if he was getting enough s=
leep, people familiar with the conversations said. While the directors woul=
dn=E2=80=99t specifically ask about substance abuse, the people said they u=
nderstood the questions to be about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s perceived drug use.=
=C2=A0

I wish that was a risk factor in the annual report.
  [2]
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CWe depend on the services of Elon Musk, our CEO and Technoki=
ng, and we are=C2=A0worried=C2=A0that he isn=E2=80=99t getting enough=C2=A0=
sleep, if you know what we mean. If he=C2=A0keeps staying up too late, that=
 may impact our business and financial results.=E2=80=9D

