   =20
      Carta
   =20
 =20

The paradigmatic 21st century business model is probably giving a product a=
way for free, or at least below cost, in order to collect data that can be =
used for lucrative targeted advertising. This is how=C2=A0most email=C2=A0w=
orks, and basically all of social media, and it has become such a staple of=
 modern business thought that companies like  WeWork and   MoviePass could =
go around being like =E2=80=9Csure we charge people below our cost for offi=
ce space or movie tickets, but see we collect=C2=A0data.=E2=80=9D
One problem with this model is that=C2=A0the better the data =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the more intimate and valuable the information you collect about your cu=
stomers =E2=80=94=C2=A0the more annoyed people will get if you use it. When=
 the ads are too targeted, it=E2=80=99s creepy and people get angry.
For instance, one product where this model seems lucrative but tricky=C2=A0=
is startup cap table management:
=09Private companies issue shares to various people (founders, employees, c=
ontractors, angel investors, venture capitalists, etc.), with various terms=
 and restrictions. The company needs to keep track of its capitalization ta=
ble=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0who owns shares, what sorts of shares they own, wha=
t restrictions they have, etc. =E2=80=94 in a robust, reliable, trustworthy=
 way. It probably doesn=E2=80=99t have the expertise to do that itself. And=
 if you mess this up you get in bad trouble.=09So there are companies =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Carta is the main one =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the business of keeping=
 these lists (startups=E2=80=99 capitalization tables) in reliable and user=
-friendly ways.=09Those lists are=C2=A0so valuable. Lots of investment bank=
ers, wealth managers and other intermediaries and service providers would a=
bsolutely=C2=A0kill=C2=A0to know, for instance, the names and holdings of e=
very Stripe or SpaceX or OpenAI shareholder.
  [3]
=C2=A0Tons of things you can do with those=C2=A0lists.=C2=A0Most notably, a=
 lot of outsiders want to=C2=A0buy=C2=A0shares of hot startups, but they ca=
n=E2=80=99t; those shares don=E2=80=99t trade in any sort of organized mark=
et. But=C2=A0if you know who owns the shares, you can call them up, see who=
 wants to sell, and then advertise=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99ve got some =
Stripe shares for sale=E2=80=9D to the potential buyers. Startup shares do =
not trade in a transparent way, and if you know who owns the shares then yo=
u can make a killing as a broker.=C2=A0

So from first principles it is tempting to, like, (1) build a great cap tab=
le management system, (2) go out to startups to sign them up and (3) have a=
 click-through user agreement where on screen=C2=A017 it is like =E2=80=9Cy=
ou authorize us to use your cap table data in any way that we want, includi=
ng calling up your shareholders to pitch them on trades.=E2=80=9D
This is, however, not how the cap table business usually goes. In fact the =
shareholders don=E2=80=99t seem to want their data used this way, and neith=
er do the companies. And this is a sensitive enough issue that the companie=
s are not going to just sign a click-through user agreement; they will actu=
ally say to the cap table company =E2=80=9Cyou will keep our shareholder li=
st confidential right?=E2=80=9D and the cap table company will have to say =
yes.
Also, having the list is not the only impediment to startup share trading: =
Often startups prohibit their shareholders from selling, or have approval a=
nd/or first refusal rights over any sales. So if you had the cap table, you=
 would look at it and see that everyone was restricted from trading, so you=
 couldn=E2=80=99t really use it to put together trades anyway.
Startups care about keeping control over their shareholder lists; the cap t=
able management product is a tool for them to exercise that control. If a c=
ap table management company=C2=A0takes that control away from them =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0if it uses its data to broker trades the company doesn=E2=80=99t w=
ant =E2=80=94=C2=A0then=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s bad service.=C2=A0
Still you see the appeal. Carta got in trouble this weekend,=C2=A0Axios=E2=
=80=99s Dan Primack reports:

Karri Saarinen, CEO of a VC-backed software startup called Linear, disclose=
d=C2=A0via social media=C2=A0that a Carta salesperson had contacted an ange=
l investor in his company, telling them that Carta had a "firm buy order" f=
or the angel's shares in Linear.
According to Saarinen, this angel investor is a family member who's never b=
een publicly disclosed and who's "hardly online."
Moreover, Linear had never been asked to approve for such a secondary sale,=
 which it legally would be required to do, and a VC source says that both L=
inear and its major investors would have had a right of first refusal.
In short, someone on Carta's "liquidity solutions" team had accessed Linear=
's confidential cap table data; leveraging the core product as lead gen for=
 a more lucrative effort. It was a massive ethical breach, no matter how di=
fferent lawyers might interpret Carta's privacy policy.
One VC told me it was akin to "Oracle using your database to share supply-c=
hain data or Salesforce using your CRM data to inquire about the state of y=
our sales leads."

Here is Carta=E2=80=99s chief executive officer=E2=80=99s  Medium post on t=
he matter, saying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m appalled we made that mistake and it=
 should never have happened.=E2=80=9D He explains that, in addition to keep=
ing the shareholder lists, Carta has its own startup brokerage business, wh=
ich, uh, which isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0supposed=C2=A0to look at the lists, but m=
an is it tempting:

CartaX is a separate product that operates as an opt-in marketplace where i=
nvestors are invited to enter bids and asks on different companies. At any =
given time we have about one hundred companies that are in the marketplace.=
 Where CartaX and the cap table business converge is if we match a trade in=
 the marketplace, we go to the company and ask if they will allow it. If th=
e company allows it, we use their cap table to execute the trade. If the co=
mpany doesn=E2=80=99t allow it, we stop the trade. We do not and will never=
 trade without company consent.
In the case of Linear and two other companies, we had an internal breach of=
 protocol and we contacted someone directly on the cap table. That never sh=
ould have happened and is absolutely a breach of our privacy protocols.

Saarinen  tweeted:

This buy order was for $2.5M, they take 2% transaction fee from the buyer a=
nd seller.=C2=A0
We pay them about $10k a year for the cap table management but this transac=
tion alone would net them $100k. So I can see the temptation.

Yes, right, the targeted advertising data from the shareholder list=C2=A0is=
 just way, way, way more valuable than charging the customer directly for k=
eeping the list.

