   =20
      Shale but green
   =20
 =20

I feel like  this is a very solvable problem?

US shale magnate Harold Hamm is leading attempts to lure an increasingly sc=
eptical younger generation to the oil and gas industry as climate concerns =
and job insecurity dent the attractiveness of the industry for graduates an=
d skilled tradespeople.
=E2=80=9CWe are going to be using oil for the next 50 years and =E2=80=98cl=
ean burning=E2=80=99 natural gas probably for the next 100 or 150 years=E2=
=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89we want to get the next generation of g=
ame-changers involved,=E2=80=9D said the businessman, who recently donated =
$50mn to establish the Hamm Institute for American Energy at Oklahoma State=
 University. =E2=80=A6
The Hamm Institute is one of a growing number of initiatives aiming to disp=
el negative perceptions of the industry. In 2022, ExxonMobil donated $16.4m=
n to universities and colleges worldwide and Chevron has helped establish a=
 jobs readiness programme in the US called SkillsReady to prepare and attra=
ct workers to the oil and gas sectors. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9C[Students have] been told for a very long time that oil and gas is=
 going away and they=E2=80=99re concerned about having long-term careers,=
=E2=80=9D said Jennifer Miskimins, head of petroleum engineering at the Col=
orado School of Mines.

Okay what you do is, you set up a new Institute for the Clean Renewable Ene=
rgy of the Future, and you encourage students to major in Green Energy, and=
 then the courses in the Green Energy major are about petroleum engineering=
? And then, at your shale company, you hire them, and you give them the job=
 title Renewable Energy Technology Engineer. This is easy stuff.
I write sometimes around here about the complex financial engineering sleig=
ht-of-hand that goes into some carbon credits and other green investing pro=
ducts. But I also write sometimes around here about the=C2=A0extremely simp=
le financial engineering sleight-of-hand=C2=A0that goes into, like, taking =
an index fund and   putting "ESG=E2=80=9D in the name, or taking an oil pip=
eline company and   putting the word =E2=80=9CGreen=E2=80=9D in the name, o=
r taking the World Coal Alliance and   putting =E2=80=9CFuture=E2=80=9D and=
 =E2=80=9CSustainable=E2=80=9D in the name. This is not, I think, mostly de=
ceptive, or at least it is not deceptive to its direct audience. The name m=
atters! You are marketing something, but the thing you are marketing is per=
ception;=C2=A0you are marketing to people who are=C2=A0marketing themselves=
 as good people.=C2=A0They want to get well-paid jobs as petroleum engineer=
s, and they want to tell their friends that they are majoring in Saving the=
 Earth and then getting jobs in Renewable Energy Technology. Just call it t=
hat!

